/gtr.ukri.org:80/projects?ref=RES-173-27-0069"><gtr:id>72A85EFD-6729-40E8-ADEB-75ADAC5459FB</gtr:id><gtr:title>A Place for Mediation in Workplace Conflict Management</gtr:title><gtr:status>Closed</gtr:status><gtr:grantCategory>Fellowship</gtr:grantCategory><gtr:grantReference>RES-173-27-0069</gtr:grantReference><gtr:abstractText>The Advisory, Conciliation and Arbitration Service (Acas) is a non-departmental body whose &amp;quot;mission is to improve organisations and working life through better employment relations? [and] help prevent or resolve both large-scale and individual disputes by providing a range of services such as conciliation, mediation and arbitration&amp;quot;. The focus of the Fellow's role is to explore workplace conflict and mediation against the backdrop of the Gibbons Review (Better Dispute Resolution: A Review of Employment Dispute Resolution in Great Britain) and mediation research/evaluation being undertaken in Acas' Research and Evaluation Section (RES).
&lt;br />
&lt;br />The Fellow will engage with this wider programme, providing peer review support to RES. His provisional agenda also includes the use of existing survey and case study evidence, together with primary data collection, to:
&lt;br />
&lt;br />
&lt;ul>
 &lt;li>appraise the state of play regarding mediation of employment disputes, possibly alongside a sectoral study;&lt;/li>
 &lt;li>expand knowledge of Employment Tribunal claims, in particular the incidence of multiple claims and the patterns and impact of representation;&lt;/li>
 &lt;li>develop an e-survey with trade union representatives relating to their strategies for resolving individual and collective disputes;&lt;/li>
 &lt;li>design a study of mediators to encapsulate mediation processes; and&lt;/li>
 &lt;li>identify areas for further research and explore funding sources.&lt;/li>
